Certainly! To display the uploaded images and notes on your webpage, you can modify the frontend JavaScript to fetch the data from the backend and dynamically update the HTML. Here's how you can do it:

### Modifying the Backend

Make sure you have your backend endpoints set up to return the notes and images properly. We already have the `/notes` endpoint that returns notes, so let's modify the code to send back image data as well.

Here's an update to the Flask backend code (specifically the `/upload-image` endpoint):

```python
@app.route('/images', methods=['GET'])
def get_images():
    user_images = mongo.db.images.find({"user": session['user']})
    images = [{"filename": img["image_name"]} for img in user_images]
    return jsonify(images), 200
```

This new endpoint retrieves the images for the logged-in user and returns them in JSON format.

### Updating the Frontend

Now update your `index.html` to include functionality that fetches and displays the notes and images.

Here’s the updated HTML and JavaScript:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Notes & Images</title>
    <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Personal Note Taking & Photo Storage</h1>
    <button onclick="window.location.href='/login'">Login with Google</button>

    <div>
        <h2>Notes</h2>
        <textarea id="noteInput" placeholder="Enter your note here..."></textarea>
        <button onclick="addNote()">Add Note</button>
        <div id="notesList"></div>
    </div>

    <div>
        <h2>Upload Image</h2>
        <input type="file" id="imageUpload">
        <button onclick="uploadImage()">Upload</button>
        <div id="imagesList"></div>
    </div>

    <script>
        $(document).ready(function() {
            loadNotes();
            loadImages();
        });

        function addNote() {
            const note = $("#noteInput").val();
            $.ajax({
                url: '/notes',
                method: 'POST',
                contentType: 'application/json',
                data: JSON.stringify({ note: note }),
                success: function(response) {
                    $("#noteInput").val('');
                    loadNotes();
                }
            });
        }

        function loadNotes() {
            $.ajax({
                url: '/notes',
                method: 'GET',
                success: function(data) {
                    $('#notesList').empty();
                    data.forEach(function(note) {
                        $('#notesList').append(`<p>${note.note}</p>`);
                    });
                }
            });
        }

        function uploadImage() {
            const file = $("#imageUpload")[0].files[0];
            const formData = new FormData();
            formData.append('file', file);
            $.ajax({
                url: '/upload-image',
                method: 'POST',
                processData: false,
                contentType: false,
                data: formData,
                success: function(response) {
                    $("#imageUpload").val('');
                    loadImages();
                }
            });
        }

        function loadImages() {
            $.ajax({
                url: '/images',
                method: 'GET',
                success: function(data) {
                    $('#imagesList').empty();
                    data.forEach(function(image) {
                        $('#imagesList').append(`<img src="uploads/${image.filename}" alt="User image" style="max-width: 200px; margin: 5px;"/>`);
                    });
                }
            });
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation of New Features:

1. **Load Notes on Page Load**: The `$(document).ready()` function calls `loadNotes()` and `loadImages()` when the page loads to fetch and display existing notes and uploaded images.

2. **Adding Notes**: The `addNote` function sends a POST request to the `/notes` endpoint. Upon success, it clears the input and reloads the notes by calling `loadNotes()`.

3. **Loading Notes**: The `loadNotes` function sends a GET request to the `/notes` endpoint and dynamically appends each note to the `#notesList`.

4. **Uploading Images**: The `uploadImage` function creates a `FormData` object to send the file to the server.

5. **Loading Images**: The `loadImages` function sends a GET request to the `/images` endpoint and displays each image in the `#imagesList` using an `<img>`

